Is there a more efficient way to write this code, or can I improve upon it in any way?

Your current code looks good and efficient. One minor improvement you can make is to replace `vector` with `vector` for the `primes` vector, since you only need to store whether each number is prime or not, not the actual value of the prime numbers. This can save memory and improve performance.
Here's the updated code:
```
#include 
#include 
using namespace std;
bool isPrime(int num) {
 if (num < 2) {
 return false;
 }
 for (int i = 2; i <= sqrt(num); i++) {
 if (num % i == 0) {
 return false;
 }
 }
 return true;
}
int main() {
 vector primes(9, true); // initialize all numbers to true
 primes[0] = primes[1] = false; // 0 and 1 are not prime
 // Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm to mark non-prime numbers
 for (int i = 2; i <= sqrt(8); i++) {
 if (primes[i]) {
 for (int j = i * i; j <= 8; j += i) {
 primes[j] = false;
 }
 }
 }
 cout << "IndextValuen";
 for (int i = 2; i <= 8; i++) {
 if (primes[i]) {
 cout << i << "t" << "Primen";
 } else {
 cout << i << "t" << "Not primen";
 }
 }
 return 0;
}
```
This code uses the Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm to mark non-prime numbers, which is more efficient than checking each number individually using the `isPrime` function. It also uses a `vector` to store whether each number is prime or not, which saves memory compared to using a `vector` to store the actual prime numbers.

